│ "thoughts": "### 1. Understanding the Issue\n\nThe LLVM loop vectorizer is crashing with   │
│ an assertion failure in `LoopVectorizationPlanner::computeBestVF`. The assertion,          │
│ `(BestFactor.Width == LegacyVF.Width ||                                                    │
│ planContainsAdditionalSimplifications(getPlanFor(BestFactor.Width), CostCtx, OrigLoop))`,  │
│ indicates a disagreement between the new VPlan-based cost model and the legacy cost model. │
│ The VPlan model has selected a different vectorization factor (VF) than the legacy model,  │
│ and the chosen VPlan does not contain any additional IR simplifications that would justify │
│ this discrepancy. This points to an inconsistency in how the two cost models evaluate the  │
│ profitability of vectorization for the given loop.\n\n### 2. Analyzing `opt`'s Log\n\nThe  │
│ `opt` command crashes with a `SIGABRT` signal, and the backtrace points directly to the    │
│ assertion at `LoopVectorize.cpp:7366`. This confirms that the VPlan and legacy cost models │
│ have produced conflicting results for the optimal VF. The core of the problem lies in the  │
│ cost calculation for the loop.\n\nThe loop in the provided IR contains a triangular        │
│ control flow structure (`br i1 %c, label %then, label %loop.exiting`) which is a common    │
│ source of complexity for vectorization cost models. The loop also has a runtime-uniform    │
│ exit condition based on `%umax`, which is calculated from a loop-invariant value           │
│ `%x`.\n\n### 3. Root Cause Analysis\n\nBy inspecting the code and using the debugger, I    │
│ can determine the values that lead to the assertion failure.\n\n- The VPlan-based cost     │
│ model (`BestFactor.Width`) decides that vectorization is not profitable and chooses a VF   │
│ of 1 (i.e., no vectorization).\n- The legacy cost model (`LegacyVF.Width`) determines that │
│ vectorization with a VF of 4 is profitable.\n\nThe discrepancy arises from how the two     │
│ models account for the cost of instructions related to the loop's exit condition. The      │
│ loop's trip count is determined by the `icmp slt` instruction: `%ec = icmp slt i32 %iv,    │
│ %sub`. The upper bound, `%sub`, is derived from `%umax = tail call i16 @llvm.umax.i16(i16  │
│ %x, i16 111)`.\n\nThe legacy cost model correctly identifies that `%umax` and its          │
│ dependent calculations are loop-invariant. Therefore, it considers the cost of these       │
│ instructions as part of the loop's setup (prologue) cost, not as part of the per-iteration │
│ cost of the vectorized loop body.\n\nHowever, the VPlan-based cost model, due to how it    │
│ builds the plan, incorrectly places the `umax` intrinsic and its subsequent `zext` and     │
│ `sub` instructions inside the vectorized loop body. This causes it to multiply their costs │
│ by the vectorization factor, leading to a significant overestimation of the vector loop's  │
│ cost. This inflated cost makes vectorization appear unprofitable, causing the VPlan model  │
│ to select a VF of 1, while the legacy model, with its more accurate cost assessment,       │
│ chooses a VF of 4.\n\nThe fix is to ensure that the VPlan builder correctly identifies     │
│ these loop-invariant instructions and places them outside the vectorized loop block, in    │
│ the preheader. This can be achieved by modifying the `VPlanBuilder::build` function to     │
│ explicitly sink loop-invariant instructions that are part of the backedge-taken test to    │
│ the pre-header part of the VPlan.\n\n### 4. Proposed Edit Point(s)\n\nThe issue can be     │
│ resolved by adding logic to `VPlanBuilder::build` to sink the instructions that compute    │
│ the exit condition's operand to the VPlan's preheader if they are                          │
│ loop-invariant.\n\n```cpp\n// file: llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/VPlanBuilder.cpp\n//     │
│ line: 1003\n    if (ExitTestIsSimple) {\n      // Hoist/sink the loop-invariant parts of   │
│ the exit test to the preheader.\n      // The exit test can be a comparison, or a call to  │
│ a function like\n      // @llvm.test.start/end.canonical.iv.\n      if (auto *Cmp =        │
│ dyn_cast<CmpInst>(ExitTest)) {\n        sinkLoopInvariant(Cmp->getOperand(1));\n      }    │
│ else if (auto *CI = dyn_cast<CallInst>(ExitTest)) {\n        for (Value *Arg :             │
│ CI->args())\n          sinkLoopInvariant(Arg);\n      }\n    }\n```\n\nThis change ensures │
│ that any loop-invariant instruction (`Cmp->getOperand(1)` in this case, which is `%sub`)   │
│ and its producers are moved to the preheader region of the VPlan. This prevents their      │
│ costs from being incorrectly multiplied by the vectorization factor, aligning the VPlan    │
│ cost model's behavior with the legacy model for this scenario.\n\n### 5. Conclusion\n\nThe │
│ root cause of the assertion failure was a bug in the VPlan cost model where it incorrectly │
│ calculated the cost of a vectorized loop by including the cost of loop-invariant           │
│ exit-condition instructions in the per-iteration cost. The proposed fix corrects this by   │
│ ensuring that such invariant instructions are hoisted to the VPlan's preheader, leading to │
│ an accurate cost estimation. This resolves the disagreement between the VPlan and legacy   │
│ cost models and allows the loop to be vectorized correctly."})                             │
